<div class="pretty">
<p>“I'm bringing you home, Jen.” I say, taking my eyes off the road for a moment to look at her. The only reply is the continued scraping of her teeth – back and forth – only interrupted by the occasional <em>crack.</em></p>
<p>I keep driving.</p>
<p>I jump when she speaks, “What's inside me? Clawing at me, chewing me.”</p>
<p>I look at her, she is still looking straight ahead, the constant grinding never-ending.</p>
<p>“I don't know,” I say.</p>
<p>“I just&#8230; need to–,” the grinding stops slowly, replaced by a small squeaking noise. I look at her again. On her shirt are dozens of bloody fragments of teeth, her jaw is still moving back and forth.</p>
<p>“I just asked him,” she speaks, “he calls himself… WAN.” She turns and looks at me. “He wants me to thank you. I am his now.”</p>
<p>“I don't&#8230; I don't understand.”</p>
<p>She finally stops sliding her jaw back and forth and grins at me, a toothless grin. As she smiles, her teeth slowly reappear one by one, with a short, wet popping noise.</p>
<p>“He says…” <em>pop, pop,</em> “he tells me to go to him. To find the pieces along the way.”</p>
<p>Her grin disappears as we arrive at her home – a small white house with red shutters. It almost seems to glow as the headlights shine on its walls.</p>
<p>I turn off the car and sit for a moment, the grinding sound to my right returning in the silence. Leaning forward on the steering wheel, I breath in and breath out in a vain attempt to stop the panicked beating in my chest. I lean back up and turn to open the door.</p>
<p>“WAN wants me. WAN needs me.” She speaks, muffled through her closed lips.</p>
<p>I shake my head and close the door, heading to the passenger side and lifting her out. She seems to weigh even less than before…</p>
<p>As I hold her, she gutturally whispers into my ear.</p>
<p>“He says he wants you too. He says that she didn't drink all the water like she was supposed to. He says he warned you. He says you knew the risks.” She opens her mouth and leans forward towards my ear, I feel her warm breath as a wad of teeth, blood, and saliva roll off of her tongue, slipping into the waiting canal, “He says you are his now.”</p>
<p>In disgust, I drop her on the ground and look down at myself, the soft yellow of the sodium bulb street-lights illuminated my body. I try to reach up, in some attempt to reach my ear, but I could not move. I see my fists are bleeding as I dig my nails into them. The musculature on my arm is straining, expanding outside my skin. My skin splits open and the red of muscle seems even more vivid with the orange light.</p>
<p>Jen pushes herself off the ground and looked at me, her movements slow and tired.</p>
<p>“Aaron?” she asks, her eyes look heavy, as if just waking up.</p>
